"This vapor is identical in composition to ice fog, with a temperature of zero (0) ℃ and 99% humidity as it exits SCP-244-1."

In an area of 99% humidity, all of the moisture in the air would be evaporated, thus invisible, thus you wouldn't get the creepy fog effect. Mist occurs once warmer air containing a lot of moisture cools down, passing the so-called "dew point" and condensing some of the air laden moisture into tiny droplets of fog. So any area with mist by definition has over 100% humidity (or has 100% humidity with further suspended liquid water, depending on how you define it).

Unless you are making this apparent contradiction a part of the artifact's strangeness, you should change the text to match. Also the measure "MJ/kg" isn't really a rate in the traditional sense, and depending on the amount of time involved the human body can indeed give off that ratio of thermal energy per kg of mass, so I think you wanted a power measurement there (Watts and the like).

As for containment, why can't they just wrap it up in something that allows no space for it to fall over and open? Like a form-fitted package? Or encase it in concrete? It seems unlikely that such a container would be overcome by the device as described, and if it does somehow have the ability to breach even that containment you might want to mention how it does so.

I'm sorry if I come off as overly critical, the science nitpicking usually brings out the most annoying of my editing habits.





