Fair enough for the second part. I was going to try and mention ways the Foundation could crack open concrete if they needed to, but that would be either unnecessary detail or ridiculous inter-SCP reference wankery, neither of which would help this article.

As for the measurement to be used, first of all watts are already a rate measurement (joule per second) so saying kW/s is odd. Besides that though, this thing is really deterred by strong sources of thermal energy, right? We have a convenient measurement for that, and it's called temperature :D. Just give the thing a temperature, say 100C, after which it avoids instead of pursues sources of heat.

As to yoric's comment and your reply, yes there are endnotes that lack the clinical tone of the normal SCP article. In my opinion the majority of them are unnecessary or even detrimental to the article. Even though they are notes tacked on to the official article, they are written by supposedly jaded professionals who deal with this sort of thing literally every day. It strains credibility (and reads awkwardly) for them to lapse into cheesy informal bickering at the end of every article despite the fact that they know it is going to be archived with the rest of the official document.

Some people have different opinions on that, which is doubtless why it is so popular. Heck I did it on first drafts of many of my articles. But I learned better, and at the very least expect to get this criticism every time you use that device in your writing here. With all that said, I don't think this article is a particularly notable offender but could benefit from some cleanup.







